<big><b>The First Human Beings</b></big>

<big><b>EARLY HUMANS</b></big>

Human beings have lived on Earth for millions of years.

The earliest humans were very different from people today.

They lived in small groups and depended on nature for survival.

They needed to find:

• Food
• Water
• Shelter
• Protection from animals


<big><b>Life as Hunters and Gatherers</b></big>

Early humans were hunters and gatherers.

They hunted animals for meat and gathered fruits, nuts, and plants.

Examples:

• Men and women worked together to find food.
• They moved from place to place looking for resources.
• They used simple tools made from stone and wood.


<big><b>The Discovery of Fire</b></big>

One of the most important discoveries was fire.

Fire helped humans:

• Cook food
• Stay warm
• Scare away wild animals
• Create light at night

Examples:

• Cooked food was easier to eat.
• People could live in colder places.


<big><b>The First Tools</b></big>

Early humans created tools to make life easier.

They used stones to make:

• Knives
• Spears
• Axes

Examples:

• Spears were used for hunting.
• Stone tools helped people cut meat and wood.


<big><b>The Beginning of Farming</b></big>

Around 12,000 years ago, some groups began farming.

Instead of moving constantly, they settled in one place.

They grew crops such as:

• Wheat
• Barley
• Rice

They also domesticated animals like:

• Dogs
• Sheep
• Goats

Examples:

• Farming allowed villages to grow.
• Food became more reliable.


<big><b>The Rise of Civilizations</b></big>

As villages grew larger, civilizations began to develop.

People built:

• Houses
• Roads
• Temples

New jobs appeared:

• Farmers
• Builders
• Traders
• Leaders

Examples:

• Trade connected different communities.
• Writing systems were developed to record information.


<big><b>Interesting Facts</b></big>

• Modern humans are called <b>Homo sapiens</b>.
• The oldest stone tools are more than 3 million years old.
• Agriculture changed human society forever.
• Early humans lived on every continent except Antarctica.


